, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"West","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and German: from Middle English, Middle High German <i>west</i> ‘west’, hence a topographic name for someone who lived to the west of a settlement, or a habitational name for someone who had migrated from further west.","Americanized form of Finnish <b>Vesterinen</b>: from the personal name <i>Vesteri</i> (a short form of   Sylvester  ) + the surname suffix <i>-nen</i>.","History: This name was brought to North America independently by many bearers in the 17th and 18th centuries. Thomas West, 12th Baron De La Warre, was captain general of Virginia in 1610–11. The state of DE is named for him. One of the earliest permanent settlers was Francis West (1606–92), who came to Duxbury, MA, from Salisbury, Wiltshire, England, in or before 1638."],"variants":[{"name":"Western","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>westerne</i> ‘western’, denoting ‘(the man from the) west’. Compare   West   and   Wester  .","Norwegian: habitational name from the farm name Vestern, found in two places, a compound of <i>vest</i> ‘west’ + <i>vin</i> ‘meadow’, denoting a farm to the west."]},{"name":"Sylvester","meanings":["English and German: from the Middle English and Latin personal name <i>Silvester</i> ‘dweller in the forest’ (a derivative of <i>silva</i> ‘wood’). The name was borne by three popes, including a contemporary of Constantine the Great, and seems to have been first used in England by clerics."]},{"name":"Westman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Birgit, Erik, Hilmer, Nels.","Swedish: ornamental or topographic name from (an altered form of) the elements <i>väst</i> ‘west’ + <i>-man</i>. It is also found in Finland.","Americanized form of German <b>Westmann</b>: variant of   West  , with the addition of Middle High German <i>man</i> ‘man’."]}]},{"name":"Clarissa","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Clarice   occasionally found in medieval documents. It was revived by  Samuel Richardson  as the name of the central character in his novel Clarissa (  1748 ) and has since remained in moderate use."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":21,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Clarissa de West was born in 1238, in Nottinghamshire, England. She had at least 2 sons with Sir John Markham. She died in 1276, in her hometown, at the age of 38."},"et":{"1238–1276":"1238–1276","1236–Male":"1236–Surnud","1264–1289":"1264–1289","–Male":"Surnud","1238":"1238","1259":"1259","1236":"1236","1289":"1289","1276":"1276","1264":"1264","about 1264":"umbes 1264","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England"},"fi":{"1238–1276":"1238–1276","1236–Male":"1236–Kuollut","1264–1289":"1264–1289","–Male":"Kuollut","1238":"1238","1259":"1259","1236":"1236","1289":"1289","1276":"1276","1264":"1264","about 1264":"noin 1264","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England"},"fr":{"1238–1276":"1238–1276","1236–Male":"1236–Décédé","1264–1289":"1264–1289","–Male":"Décédé","1238":"1238","1259":"1259","1236":"1236","1289":"1289","1276":"1276","1264":"1264","about 1264":"environ 1264","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary"